arch:property.oc:show_val: Phase VII: Roman mid CE 2nd c. collapse and repairs. Aboveground canalization cut into the bedrock in the south and east. Installation of the low walls at the south ends of the East and West Walkways. Bench built along the south face of the South Corridor Wall. The floor of Room A is built up with purple sandstone bedding and low blocking wall. Room A is restructured as an animal shelter with tethering holes cut alongside the trough. Entrance to the Paradesios is blocked. A drain in the Forecourt is repaired and appointed with ceramic pipes for additional aboveground canalization.
1.65 m north south -by- 1.65 m east west.

Locus 33 is the elevated channel following the extent of the channel room, in front of each of the niches. The course of the channel begins at the basin (Locus 34), where a circular depression catches water, leading into a curved channel which extends along the north, west, and south edges of the floor in front of the niches, until shifting 90 degrees to the south and dumping the water into the southeast niche of the bathroom. The channel is carved into three long ashlars, one on each side, which is diagonally dressed on the exterior facing the floor (the edges of the ashlars facing into the niches are roughly hewn). The channel itself is 8.5 cm wide, with a border of ~14 cm on either side, except at the southeast, where the channel takes a 90 degree turn and the raised border only takes a 45 degree turn, forming a triangle. On the base of the exterior face on the west section of the channel, there is a small drain which would have allowed water that collected on the floor of the bathroom to run off into the niche behind the channel (there is no connection between the drain and the channel itself). Like the floor of the room, the ashlars are laid in hydraulic plaster. This channel seems to be an aesthetic way of disposing of the water that flowed into the basin. Clearly a central part of the bathroom, the channel is phased to Stage 3.
Additions to the Complex, including the small reservoir, the bathroom and the anteroom.
